					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    How to win with a rogue. Advanced PvP tactics and rogue tricks for all races.</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:cbrigham@students.wisc.edu">Helio Naelyrr</a> | 
		            2/21/2000 5:48:57 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">This guide is not for newbies. If you want info on where to hunt at what level or other skill that any player of Everquest must know to survive,, it is not here.<BR>
A rogue on a PvP server, in the hands of a nimble-fingered quick-minded player, is the deadliest class one can choose. Some may disagree, but I shall show you<BR>
the truth within the shadows. What follows is a lengthy description of tactics and strategies for a rogue of any race.<BR>
Rogue Skills<BR>
Sneak and Hide. Levels 1 and 3. In combination these will allow a rogue to move, unseen and unheard by all NPC's and PC's except those with see invisible,<BR>
with a decreased movement rate = a slow walk. Know who can see you.<BR>
Character classes with the spell: see invis or it's equal are: WIZ NEC ENC MAG SHD although SKs don't get it until level 22.<BR>
     Useful when traveling, keep your eyes peeled for enemies and go unseen if a mob gets too close. Also for passing through city gates or other KoS areas. If you have to Hide in a hurry, try hitting Sneak first, it will slow you down making it easier and faster to stop moving for the Hide.<BR>
     When fighting creatures, use these skills to gain the first strike, usually a backstab. When grouped, if you are &quot;pulling&quot; use this if there is time or throw a throwing weapon if the mob is moving. Now hide also allows you to Evade, which has the effect of lowering the enemy's aggression toward the rogue. Since rogues can't Hide while being attacked, either you will get lucky and it will miss enough for you to Hide and maybe Evade, or you run fast enough to avoid attacks, then stop and Hide when you are not moving. Hopefully the mob will turn on a different party member, thus letting you escape if wounded or if not -- pierce its exposed back.<BR>
     Rogues seem to be one of the most hated classes by NPC merchants. But wily are we, for if a merchant cannot see or hear who it is dealing with, it is Indifferent. To transact with ANY merchant or banker, regardless of faction, Sneak while behind it.<BR>
     The Consider will always be indifferent. Use this for better prices from merchants that WILL sell to you but have a worse than indifferent attitude, and you will get better prices. Use it to bank in the nearest city, regardless of what race's city it is. But be careful:<BR>
     Several things can make you visible without warning, the Hide button will still be grey. Rightclicking on a corpse makes you visible whether you loot it, or you can't loot that corpse at this time. Interacting with a merchant makes you visible. Being attacked in any way makes you visible. Bard songs make you visible, as does almost every spell, good or bad. Pickpocket makes you visible as well. <BR>
      In PvP, Hide can be used to avoid a potential attacker, or to close in on an unsuspecting victim. Sneak is wonderful since most casters' only way to know if something is close is to hear it. In combat it can be useful against a non-spell class. However, any caster, with or without see invis, can simply cast one spell on you (They still have you targeted) and make you visible again, probably before it allows you to get in backstab position or bind a wound. I do not recommend using these skills during a PvP fight unless trying to escape; even a warrior can stay<BR>
moving enough to make it useless...if he's smart.<BR>
   Pick Lock. Level 6. Useful in dungeons that need keys. Leftclick on a locked door to pick the lock; you must have your lockpicks on the cursor. This is extremely hard to practice outside of the guildhall. Getting through a door that someone else can't open can be a lifesaver if they are PKing you.<BR>
    Pick Pocket. Level 7. This can be used for extra cash, even during combat if you just toggle autoattack of for a second. Undead and animals have no pockets to pick, don't waste your time. Red monsters will almost assuredly catch you, but pickpocketing another (high-level?) party's mobs can be profitable and safe since it would be busy. A weapon the mob is holding, or armor it's wearing, cannot be pickpocketed. Pickpocketed cash is drawn from a monster's total cash -- and if you are grouped, that is almost like GASP! stealing from your party members' share.<BR>
Use this to get money after you die in case you need supplies on the return trip.<BR>
     Backstab. Level 10. The skill that makes rogues deadly. When fighting an NPC: solo -- get a group. Grouped -- always position yourself behind the mob. When/If it turns to attack you, Hide sometimes works to Evade their anger. If you back away from the battle (to Throwing range?) the mob will usually attack someone closer. Wait to return to battle, not attacking, until the mob has been HIT by at least one attack. Then if you are fast enough, you can slip in quickly and backstab. Of course the mob<BR>
will turn on you immediately, and it will be harder to escape it again. If you are too slow with the attack, the monster will usually turn on you anyway since you are in its range again. This acts as an extra normal attack if the target is facing you. See below for PvP uses.<BR>
    Safe Fall. Level 12. Useful when in rocky or hilly terrain. It will prevent any falling damage from running too fast over sand dunes or hilltops. You can escape creatures easily using this skill if there is a cliff nearby. A mob will not follow you over the drop off if it<BR>
is of any really good height. They backtrack to the next fastest way down, almost always affording you enough time to escape. The same trick can be used to avoid PC attackers, though they CAN come after you if they think it's worth taking the damage.<BR>
     Apply and Make Poison. Level 18 and 20. This is the second skill that makes rogues deadly. Most rogue poisons are made by rogues, though some are looted. The effects vary from huge direct damage, to powerful DoTs, to stat and resistance penalties. Looted poisons have special effects. Applying a poison is done by right-clicking it(must be sitting). This takes a few rounds. In actuality it poisons your primary weapon slot; a rogue cannot give poisoned weapons to other characters. Only Piercing weapons are poisonable. The poison does not survive zoning or camping, and is used on the first strike you make. Poison strength (i.e. damage) is a function of your level.<BR>
     Making Poison requires a mortar and pestle(container). Every attempt requires a poison vial of appropriate quality, a suspension, and various different lootable components. A true rogue is also a master of pottery, as poison vials are only player-made. <BR>
     Poison is extremely powerful, and not surprisingly also time-consuming. Collecting components proves to be the worst part, next to pottery and cost in platinum. A rogue could gain levels solo if he had a dose of poison for every mob he fought that was blue or harder. Since nobody has 100 years to level a rogue, we save it for &quot;occasions.&quot; A particularly hard enemy will go down faster with poison when grouped, maybe saving lives. Personally my occasions are never with mobs, always PCs. <BR>
     In PvP, if you can apply poison before a fight or a murder you can be unstoppable. For a level 18 rogue, snake poison will do 108 damage over 6 rounds. Unless the target is over 4 levels higher than you, this will be a crippling blow. Certain poisons can lower the target's STR and/or AGI, possibly making them encumbered and slower. There exists a poison with an effect equivalent to the spell: Snare. If your mark has low HPs, poisoned<BR>
backstab may kill him or her before they can react!<BR>
     Instill Doubt. Level 22. This skill takes about 4 rounds to take effect. At the end of that time, you either fail, target out of range, or the enemy succombs, taking a small non-melee hit<BR>
and being forced to turn it's back on you and run away. A message is given to you when the fear wears off. This skill was eliminated for PvP fights. Do NOT use this skill in any crowded place, even when practicing. If the mob your group is fighting takes off suddenly,<BR>
and at full speed unlike when it's almost dead, it will almost assuredly reach friends before it can be rooted or killed -- in Mistmoore or Unrest this will get your party waxed.<BR>
     Disarm. Level 27. This is somewhat useful against creatures with weapons in their hands; if disarmed they will not re-arm the weapon, doing less damage. Also the weapon is then pickpocket-able. In PvP combat, the disarmed weapon will be put in the first empty inventory slot, possibly creating confusion and mad searching while you stand behind <BR>
the weaponless target and carve.<BR>
     Rogue combat skills are Dodge, Parry, Double Attack, Dual Wield, and Riposte.<BR>
     Keep stocked! with bandages and throwing weapons, and poison if you can. <BR>
     Bind Wound is important for a rogue, max it out as soon as you can. Max is 100 for rogues, at which point it heals 25 HPs per bandaid, plus about 3 HPs while you are standing there. Much better than the 9 HPs you get for sitting.<BR>
     Throwing is also a potent weapon for a rogue. Archery can also be powerful, and even better in cases that long range is needed. But at level 12 rogues are able to critical hit with any<BR>
throwing weapon, doing 5x normal damage. If a throwing weapon hits a target in the back, the possible critical does about 10x normal damage. This makes the knives or shuriken much better than a bow and arrow. <BR>
     Hitting a mob with a knife or shuriken will pull it if it is escaping your backstab range, and if your range is long enough you may be able to get two or three hits before it closes the<BR>
gap. Also throw at the mobs when you are badly wounded in a fight. Unless it is REALLY mad or you are REALLY low on HPs, it will not chase you down and you can contribute a few shuriken and maybe a nice critical.<BR>
     In PvP, throwing is a rogue's bastion of defense against a spellcaster. If you cannot reach <BR>
a caster before he finishes his spell, toss a shuriken -- it may interrupt, and if it criticals it WILL interrupt. If he tries again immediately, you are either already within range to pierce or your shuriken will recycle within a second or so, probably in time to interrupt the spell again. Of course, if the target is running away, he will have shuriken hitting him in the back and maybe doing ten times normal damage.<BR>
  PVP ASSASSINS<BR>
A rogue, with backstab as his ONLY weapon, could beat any other class if he was quick enough. Set up your turn left and turn right keys so you can reach them with the same hand you hit Hotkeys with. Get in the habit of fighting with your hand on the mouse. Holding the right<BR>
mousebutton while moving the mouse changes your character's heading and direction of view. If you then click the left mousebutton you will begin running forward. Right hand on the mouse, left one on the turn keys and CTRL. Holding CTRL will make you shuffle sideways instead of turning. Thus you begin to see the circle of death...a rogue that is shuffling sideways and running forward at the same time will be faster and more unpredictable than normal. &quot;Suddenly the rogue you were just charging at slipped to your right flank, and try as you might, you can't<BR>
turn fast enough to catch a glimpse again and OUCH! he was BEHIND me?!?&quot; When fighting, you must continually be moving. If your opponent is a spellcaster, chase him until he tries to cast; then move behind him and stay until he moves or turns to face you. If he is a fighter type, make passes at him, turning attack on and off every time. If backstab is available, a quick shove of the mouse while holding the right button down will spin you around<BR>
180 degrees. If you can time it right, you will make a pass at the target, then at the moment of impact turn around to see : his back!<BR>
     Other important things to keep in mind are: poison; if you can apply it before fighting do it! Always throw a shuriken if the target is out of range of melee; your melee attack will still be primed and ready to go off, even though the missile button is grey. If you are attacking someone nsuspecting, begin by applying poison. Then get to very short missile range(behind them of course), and throw. Immediately run forward and backstab and attack together; he might be standing up after the shuriken hits, but it is worth the possible critical, and he probably wont react before you can backstab.<BR>
   For any non-spellcasting class, a PvP essential is the Egg Shaped Pumice. It can be bought at any magic store, which are found in most cities, for under 20 pp. It carries 5 charges of Nullify<BR>
Magic. When fighting a spellcaster that roots or snares you, or casts a DoT on you, rightclick the pumice stone after targeting yourself and ALL enchantments are gone. If the opponent seems to be buffed, you can debuff ALL their stuff like SoW and HP buffs. If you are fighting a shaman, for example, use the stone RIGHT AWAY because you know a shaman has a LOT of buffs.<BR>
     Use Disarm as much as possible in PvP; if he has to go searching his bags for his sword, he will not be watching where you are(behind him).<BR>
     The way I see it is this: a rogue can beat a non-caster class hands down. They cannot compete with backstab. Hybrid classes prove a little more difficult, with spells like Snare, <BR>
Engulfing Darkness(slows movement), and Blindness, but interrupting their spells works, and the pumice stone is there for backup. Other spellcasters present almost no problem as far as melee is concerned, but for true PvP supremacy a rogue wants magic resistant armor; some spells can be devastating if they only get that ONE spell off; i.e. Mesmerize.<BR>
     A rogue can outdamage any class, IF it lands all its backstabs. And although that may be difficult in PvP combat, it is possible. I have shown you how. For evil or for good, I hope you have benefited from it.<BR>
<BR>
Helio Naelyrr,<BR>
Master Assassin of Royal House Naelyrr of Neriak<BR>
Officer, Order of the Black Rose
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
